sday.

 =20
   =20
      Covid and insider trading (1)
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a few   times about the effect of working from home on fin=
ancial crime. You could imagine it going either way: Being out of the offic=
e might cause you to do more crime, because you are less closely observed b=
y bosses and compliance, or more crime, because you are not around peer pre=
ssure to do crime. Empirically, though,=C2=A0the answer seems to be =E2=80=
=9Cless crime.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That said, there is one classic form of financial crime that I=C2=A0think=
=C2=A0would have to be increased by work-from-home? That form of financial =
crime is =E2=80=9Clooking at your girlfriend=E2=80=99s computer to see what=
 high-stakes deals she is working on,
  [1]
 and then insider trading on them.=E2=80=9D People love that one. If your g=
irlfriend mostly works from her law firm=E2=80=99s or investment bank=E2=80=
=99s office, but logs in at night=C2=A0or does weekend conference calls on =
live deals, you might pick up some information to trade on, though she migh=
t remember to use code names when you=E2=80=99re in earshot and lock her co=
mputer when she steps away. But if she works from home all day every day in=
 your one-bedroom apartment, you are just far more likely=C2=A0to know what=
 she is working on. And if you are inclined to trade on it,  you will:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Thursday] announced insider trading=
 charges against Jordan Meadow, a registered representative for a New York-=
based broker-dealer, and Steven Teixeira, the Chief Compliance Officer of a=
n international payment processing company, in connection with their tradin=
g based on material nonpublic information that Teixeira obtained from his g=
irlfriend=E2=80=99s laptop while she was working at home during the COVID-1=
9 pandemic.
The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that Teixeira accessed nonpublic inform=
ation on possible upcoming mergers and acquisitions of public companies fro=
m the laptop of his girlfriend, who was employed at a prominent New York-ba=
sed investment bank. As alleged, Teixeira then used the information to purc=
hase call options on several issuers ahead of the announcement of the deals=
 and tipped the information to his friends, including Meadow, so that they =
could trade as well. The scheme allegedly generated illicit profits of appr=
oximately $28,600 for Teixeira, while Meadow made more than $730,000. Addit=
ionally, according to the complaint, Meadow recommended trades to his broke=
rage customers based on the material nonpublic information from Teixeira, r=
esulting in millions of dollars in profits for them and hundreds of thousan=
ds of dollars in commissions for Meadow.
=E2=80=9COur complaint alleges brazen betrayals of trust by Teixeira, who m=
isappropriated information from his girlfriend=E2=80=99s laptop to make a q=
uick buck, and by industry-veteran Meadow, who was all too eager to use the=
 information to line his pockets,=E2=80=9D said Scott Thompson, the Associa=
te Regional Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Philadelphia Regional Office. =E2=
=80=9CWe will continue to pursue and prosecute insider trading where approp=
riate to hold people accountable for their actions.=E2=80=9D

There are also  criminal charges. Always the compliance officers, always th=
e call options. The girlfriend was an executive assistant at the investment=
 bank (reportedly   Morgan Stanley),  where she =E2=80=9Cwas responsible fo=
r, among other things, scheduling meetings of the Investment Bank=E2=80=99s=
 valuation and fairness=C2=A0committees concerning potential transactions i=
nvolving the Investment Bank=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=9D:
Deal teams working on transactions provided the Executive Assistant with sc=
heduling request forms for valuation and fairness committee meetings. These=
 forms included the names of the companies participating in, and the materi=
al terms relating to, the proposed deals. The Executive Assistant created a=
nd sent calendar invitations for the meetings, attaching the scheduling req=
uest forms to the invitations.=C2=A0
And:
Teixeira accessed the Executive Assistant=E2=80=99s laptop while she was aw=
ay=E2=80=94either out of the room or away from the apartment entirely. Usin=
g his access, Teixeira reviewed the Executive Assistant=E2=80=99s Outlook a=
pplication to find valuation and fairness committee meetings relating to me=
rgers and acquisitions of public companies.=C2=A0He then reviewed the attac=
hment=C2=A0containing the party names and material terms of potential trans=
actions involving the Investment Bank=E2=80=99s clients.
Sure, right, of course. The executive assistant for the fairness committee =
is far more useful, for insider trading, than a high-powered investment ban=
ker would be: The banker sees mostly her own deals; the committee assistant=
 sees just enough information on every deal.
Also there is a great information-security detail here.=C2=A0The bank was c=
areful about remote access to data, to prevent exactly this sort of thing:
The Investment Bank=E2=80=99s online portal for employees working remotely =
locked automatically after a period of inactivity. The system could detect =
that an employee was not typing or moving their mouse, for example, and wou=
ld require the employee to log in again to access the Investment Bank=E2=80=
=99s files.=C2=A0
This security system had a downside, though, which is that it is=C2=A0annoy=
ing. Nobody wants to be logged out of their remote work every time they go =
to the bathroom. So:
Teixeira provided the Executive Assistant with a device that moved the Exec=
utive Assistant=E2=80=99s mouse while she was away from her computer. This =
device simulated user activity and prevented the Investment Bank=E2=80=99s =
online portal from detecting that the Executive Assistant was away from her=
 computer, which would otherwise cause the system to lock and require the E=
xecutive Assistant to log in to access the Investment Bank=E2=80=99s files.
So she could go to the bathroom without having to log back in, and also he =
could steal her bank=E2=80=99s information and insider trade on it. The tri=
ck with information security is that you have to make your security measure=
s strong enough to defeat criminals, but not so strong that they annoy your=
 employees into disabling them.=C2=A0

