   =20
      Covid and insider trading (2)
   =20
 =20

A more straightforward sort of  Covid-driven insider trading:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Thursday] announced insider trading=
 charges against Amit Dagar, a former Pfizer Inc. employee, and his close f=
riend and business partner, Atul Bhiwapurkar, for trading in advance of the=
 company=E2=80=99s November 5, 2021, announcement that a randomized, double=
-blind study of its COVID-19 antiviral treatment, Paxlovid, was successful.=
 Following that announcement in which Pfizer=E2=80=99s CEO referred to the =
news as a =E2=80=9Cgame-changer=E2=80=9D in the global efforts to =E2=80=9C=
halt the devastation=E2=80=9D of the pandemic, the company=E2=80=99s stock =
price increased by nearly 11 percent, the largest single-day price move in =
the stock since 2009.
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, Dagar was a senior statistical pr=
ogram lead for the Paxlovid drug trial, which began in July 2021 as part of=
 the company=E2=80=99s efforts to address the global health pandemic. On th=
e day before the Paxlovid announcement, the complaint alleges, Dagar learne=
d material, nonpublic information about the success of the trial. Specifica=
lly, the SEC alleges that Dagar=E2=80=99s supervisor informed him via chat =
that =E2=80=9Cwe got the outcome,=E2=80=9D there was a =E2=80=9Clot of work=
 lined up,=E2=80=9D and that there would be a =E2=80=9Cpress release tomorr=
ow,=E2=80=9D to which Dagar responded with =E2=80=9Coh really=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Ckind of exciting.=E2=80=9D Several hours after that exchange, Daga=
r allegedly purchased short term, out-of-the-money Pfizer call options, inc=
luding options that expired the very next day, and then tipped Bhiwapurkar,=
 who also purchased similar call options in Pfizer. The complaint alleges t=
hat Dagar=E2=80=99s and Bhiwapurkar=E2=80=99s trading generated approximate=
ly $214,395 and $60,300 respectively in illicit profits, which amounted to =
one-day investment returns of 2,458 percent and 791 percent.
The case originated from the SEC=E2=80=99s Market Abuse Unit=E2=80=99s Anal=
ysis and Detection Center, which uses data analysis tools to detect suspici=
ous trading patterns.
=E2=80=9CAs alleged in our complaint, Amit Dagar misused his access to conf=
idential clinical trial results to enrich himself and his friend, Atul Bhiw=
apurkar,=E2=80=9D said Joseph Sansone, Chief of the Market Abuse Unit. =E2=
=80=9CDagar and Bhiwapurkar allegedly leveraged this information by trading=
 out-of-the-money call options to generate massive one-day returns. Thanks =
to our surveillance, the defendants must now face the consequences of their=
 greed.=E2=80=9D

There are also criminal charges. Always the call options.
But come on! This was not some random financial windfall for Pfizer; this w=
as a=C2=A0Covid treatment. Be a little more creative! On Nov. 5, 2021, Pfiz=
er announced this trial result and its stock went up 11%. That day, Royal C=
aribbean Cruises Ltd.=E2=80=99s stock was up 8%. Carnival Corp. was up 9%.=
=C2=A0Delta Air Lines Inc. was up 8%. Wynn Resorts Ltd. was up 6%. Zoom Vid=
eo Communications Inc. was down 6%. =E2=80=9CA game-changing Covid treatmen=
t will be good for the stocks of cruise-ship companies, airlines and casino=
s and bad for work-from-home stocks=E2=80=9D was about as obvious a thesis =
as =E2=80=9Ca game-changing Covid treatment will be good for the stock of t=
he company that discovers it=E2=80=9D; certainly I was banging on about thi=
s in  2020 and   2021. If you happened to know about that game-changing res=
ult a day in advance,=C2=A0because you worked for Pfizer and your boss told=
 you the results, insider trading in short-term out-of-the-money call optio=
ns in your own personal account is the most=C2=A0direct=C2=A0way to profit =
from the news, sure, but also the most direct way to get caught.
Oh but if you traded Royal Caribbean options! If you bought a bunch of Delt=
a calls and hedged by selling a bunch of Zoom calls!=C2=A0That would be int=
eresting:
=09It would work. You could reasonably have predicted how those stocks woul=
d move on the Paxlovid news, and in fact they did move that way.=09It might=
 not be illegal? We have   talked a   lot about =E2=80=9Cshadow trading,=E2=
=80=9D when employees of one company use news that they learn about that co=
mpany to trade=C2=A0other=C2=A0stocks that will move in predictable ways on=
 their company=E2=80=99s news. The SEC doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0like=C2=A0it, a=
nd=C2=A0brought   one notable shadow-trading case=C2=A0in 2021, but the law=
 is less clear here than it is when you trade your own company=E2=80=99s st=
ock.
  [2]
=C2=A0(Not legal advice!)=C2=A0=09They might not catch you: =E2=80=9CCheck =
for Pfizer employees who traded Pfizer call options right before Pfizer ann=
ounced its biggest news in years=E2=80=9D is a no-brainer for the SEC; =E2=
=80=9Ccheck for Pfizer employees who traded Wynn Resorts call options right=
 before Pfizer announced its biggest news in years=E2=80=9D is=C2=A0not as =
obvious. (Not crime-detection-avoidance advice!)=09If they=C2=A0did=C2=A0ca=
tch you and bring a case, I would be more impressed by your gumption, and h=
ave more fun writing about it. (Not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, I don=E2=80=99t =
want to encourage you to do crimes. But conditional on you doing crimes, I =
do want to encourage you to do clever, interesting crimes.)


