   =20
      SoftBank
   =20
 =20

If you have a thesis that artificial intelligence will reshape the world an=
d revolutionize every industry, how should you invest? Some options:
=09Invest in AI companies, companies that are working to develop AI technol=
ogy. Presumably they=E2=80=99ll find a way to make money with it.=09Invest =
in chip companies, betting that the rise of AI will lead to rising demand f=
or powerful microchips. A sell-shovels-in-a-gold-rush strategy.=09Invest in=
  pizza delivery startups, betting that the rise of AI will create new poss=
ibilities for increased efficiency of pizza delivery, and that your portfol=
io of pizza-delivery startups will capture the upside. I dunno, man.

Today the Wall Street Journal has a funny and rather cruel story about how =
SoftBank Group went all-in on artificial intelligence in 2018, invested $14=
0 billion in the theme, and somehow =E2=80=A6=C2=A0missed it =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0entirely?

=E2=80=9CWe are not just recklessly making investments,=E2=80=9D [SoftBank =
CEO Masayoshi] Son told investors in 2018. =E2=80=9CWe are focusing on one =
theme, which is AI.=E2=80=9D
Despite the unprecedented spending spree that Son in 2020 said would make S=
oftBank =E2=80=9Cthe investment company for the AI revolution,=E2=80=9D one=
 of the world=E2=80=99s most prolific tech investors has missed out on the =
frenzy in generative AI, the red-hot subsector in which products such as Ch=
atGPT learn from huge datasets to create unique text or images.
The Tokyo-based conglomerate has invested in just one of the 26 generative =
AI startups valued at more than $1 billion, according to PitchBook. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0SoftBank missed out on huge gains at AI-focused chip maker Nvidia:=
 The Tokyo-based investor put around $4 billion into the company in 2017, o=
nly to sell its shares in 2019. Nvidia stock is up about 10 times since.=C2=
=A0

It is possible that the problem is that Son was=C2=A0too optimistic about A=
I:

In quirky investor presentations that featured diagrams with dinosaurs and =
steam engines, the SoftBank CEO said AI would =E2=80=9Credefine all industr=
ies=E2=80=9D and usher in a powerful new wave of the information revolution=
 that began with computers=E2=80=94language similar to that many CEOs have =
begun using in recent months. ...
During the years that SoftBank was investing, it generally avoided companie=
s focused specifically on developing AI technology. Instead, it poured mone=
y into companies that Son said were leveraging AI and would benefit from it=
s growth. For example, it put billions of dollars into numerous self-drivin=
g car tech companies, which tend to use AI to help learn how humans drive a=
nd react to objects on the road. ...
Son told investors that AI would power huge expansions at numerous companie=
s where, years later, the benefits are unclear or nonexistent. In 2018, he =
highlighted AI at real-estate agency Compass, now-bankrupt construction com=
pany Katerra, and office-rental company WeWork, which he said would use AI =
to analyze how people communicate and then sell them products.

Intuitively a thesis like =E2=80=9CAI will redefine all industries=E2=80=9D=
 gets expressed by=C2=A0investing in all industries, picking the companies =
in each industry that will use AI the best, not investing in generative-AI =
developers. If you go around saying in public =E2=80=9Cwe think that AI wil=
l transform every industry and we plan to invest absolute gobs of money alo=
ng those lines,=E2=80=9D then perhaps someone building a generative-AI comp=
any will come to you and ask you for some of that money.=C2=A0But=C2=A0defi=
nitely=C2=A0people who are building real-estate agencies or construction co=
mpanies or office-rental companies or pizza-delivery companies will say =E2=
=80=9Chuh, the guy with all the money wants to invest in AI transforming ev=
ery industry, let=E2=80=99s get some of that money,=E2=80=9D and they will =
add slides to their decks like =E2=80=9CHow We Will Use AI To Transform Piz=
za Delivery=E2=80=9D with clip art of a robot and a pizza,=C2=A0and your ey=
es will light up when you see that slide and you will say =E2=80=9Csee=C2=
=A0this=C2=A0is what I am talking=C2=A0about, AI is gonna transform all the=
 industries, here=E2=80=99s $375 million.=E2=80=9D
By the way the bull case here is that he was just early, and SoftBank reall=
y did manage to pick all the companies that will do the best job of deployi=
ng AI to redefine their industries, and in 10 years all of us will work out=
 of WeWorks because WeWork is uniquely good at using AI models to, you know=
, adjust the air conditioning and dynamically price desk space and whatever=
. The real upshot of the computer revolution is that every company became a=
 tech company, and I suppose the real upshot of the AI revolution=C2=A0migh=
t be that every company becomes an AI company, and some will get there fast=
er than others. I don=E2=80=99t have any=C2=A0reason=C2=A0to think that Son=
 did pick all the right winners, but it is perhaps too early to tell.
Elsewhere in industries getting transformed by AI:

The boom in demand for high-end chips powering the rise of artificial intel=
ligence has given new life to some of the survivors of the last tech-hype c=
ycle: cryptocurrency miners.
During the crypto upsurge, Satoshi Spain sold and leased out hundreds of so=
uped-up computers=E2=80=94known as mining rigs=E2=80=94equipped with powerf=
ul graphics chips. Then, as many of them sat idle starting last year becaus=
e of the decline of mining currencies, the Spanish company began helping it=
s customers retool the machines for AI.
Today, Satoshi Spain=E2=80=99s machines are handling AI workloads for start=
ups, universities and individual developers in Europe.
=E2=80=9CYou can still make money from your mining rig,=E2=80=9D Satoshi Sp=
ain founder Alejandro Ib=C3=A1=C3=B1ez de Pedro said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=
 mining 2.0.=E2=80=9D

It would be very funny if, completely by accident,=C2=A0the big winners fro=
m the AI boom were crypto miners.

