      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Well, look, if=C2=A0I=C2=A0were the newly hired chief executive officer of =
a social media company, and if the directors and shareholders who brought m=
e in as CEO had told me that my main mission was to turn around the company=
=E2=80=99s precarious financial situation by improving our position with ad=
vertisers, and if I spent my  first few weeks reassuring advertisers and re=
building relationships and talking up our site=E2=80=99s unique audience an=
d powerful engagement, and then one day my head of software engineering cam=
e to me and said =E2=80=9Chey boss, too many people were too engaged with t=
oo many posts, so I=C2=A0had to limit everyone=E2=80=99s ability to view po=
sts on our site, just FYI,=E2=80=9D I would =E2=80=A6=C2=A0probably =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0fire ... him?
I mean I suppose I might ask questions like =E2=80=9CIs this because of som=
e technological limitation on our system? Is it because you were monkeying =
with the code without understanding it? Is it because you   tried to stop p=
eople from reading the site without logging in,
  [3]
 and  messed up and stopped them from reading the site even when they logge=
d in? Is it because you fired and  demoralized too many engineers so no one=
 was left to keep the systems running normally? Is it because you forgot to=
 pay the  cloud bills? Is it because deep down you don=E2=80=99t like it wh=
en people read posts on our site and you want to stop them, or you don=E2=
=80=99t like relying on ad revenue and want to sabotage my ability to sell =
ads?=E2=80=9D Those are all interesting questions, and I suppose having the=
 answers would help my=C2=A0new=C2=A0head of software engineering fix whate=
ver this guy broke. But no matter what the answers are, this guy=E2=80=99s =
gotta go. If you are in charge of the software engineers at a social media =
site, and you make it so that people can=E2=80=99t read the site, that=E2=
=80=99s bad.
Anyway something very funny  happened at Twitter this weekend:

Twitter began limiting how many posts users can read on its platform, an un=
usual move that came as owner Elon Musk says he is fighting companies tryin=
g to use its data for developing artificial intelligence programs.=C2=A0
Musk on Saturday detailed the temporary changes, which involved limiting un=
verified accounts to reading just 600 posts a day while verified accounts=
=E2=80=94those paying a monthly subscription=E2=80=94can read 6,000 posts d=
aily. He later announced multiple increases to the number of allowed posts.
=E2=80=9CTo address extreme levels of data scraping & system manipulation, =
we=E2=80=99ve applied the following temporary limits,=E2=80=9D Musk tweeted=
. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s unprecedented as far as I know since the time of=E2=
=80=9D internet bulletin boards, Jason Goldman, a former Twitter executive =
who has been critical of Musk=E2=80=99s stewardship, said about the limits.=
 =E2=80=9CTo set limits so low that it renders the site unusable to average=
 users is just the latest in the purely extractive approach the new ownersh=
ip is taking.=E2=80=9D

Oh man! Musk, the head of Twitter's  software and servers teams, is gonna b=
e in so much trouble when his boss, Twitter CEO Linda Yaccarino, gets to th=
e office today.
Oh I kid, I kid, but what a weird job that must be. The CEO job I mean. The=
 software-and-servers job isn=E2=80=99t that weird =E2=80=94=C2=A0he=E2=80=
=99s in charge of a website=C2=A0=E2=80=94 but he manages to make it weird.
Also:

As the ramification of Musk=E2=80=99s data battle became clear Saturday, so=
me users complained about being limited.=C2=A0
One user tweeted: =E2=80=9CYour addiction is about to be broken. We will al=
l be free. See you guys at the park.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CTouch grass again,=E2=80=9D Musk tweeted in reply.

Ha ha ha!  Yes! Musk is limiting access to Twitter in order to break its us=
ers=E2=80=99 addiction and free them to touch grass.=C2=A0He has correctly =
diagnosed the problem (Twitter users are too obsessed with it)=C2=A0and imp=
lemented a solution (don=E2=80=99t let them see too many tweets). Of course=
 to do this he had to become completely obsessed with Twitter, devote himse=
lf full-time to running it, tweet constantly and sink tens of billions of d=
ollars of his own money into buying Twitter and then breaking it. He has sa=
crificed so much himself so that people like me can spend a bit less time o=
n Twitter; he has taken the burden of Twitter addiction from millions of us=
ers and put it all on himself. Thanks!
In=C2=A0other news:

If you thought that a cage fight between two of the world=E2=80=99s richest=
 men was just a far-fetched social media stunt, think again.
Over the past 10 days, [Ultimate Fighting Championship President Dana]=C2=
=A0White said he, Mr. Musk and [Mark] Zuckerberg =E2=80=94 aided by adviser=
s =E2=80=94 have negotiated behind the scenes and are inching toward physic=
al combat. While there are no guarantees a match will happen, the broad con=
tours of an event are taking shape, said Mr. White and three people with kn=
owledge of the discussions.

People keep emailing to ask about, like, the fiduciary duties and securitie=
s-law=C2=A0disclosure issues here, but I=E2=80=99m gonna wait until they=E2=
=80=99re in the octagon before I worry about that stuff.

