ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> happened at Twitter =
this weekend</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Twitter began limiting how many posts users ca=
n read on its platform, an unusual move that came as owner Elon Musk says h=
e is fighting companies trying to use its data for developing artificial in=
telligence programs.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk on Saturday detailed the temporary change=
s, which involved limiting unverified accounts to reading just 600 posts a =
day while verified accounts=E2=80=94those paying a monthly subscription=E2=
=80=94can read 6,000 posts daily. He later announced multiple increases to =
the number of allowed posts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CTo address extreme levels of data scr=
aping &amp; system manipulation, we=E2=80=99ve applied the following tempor=
ary limits,=E2=80=9D Musk tweeted. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s unprecedented as far as =
I know since the time of=E2=80=9D internet bulletin boards, Jason Goldman, =
a former Twitter executive who has been critical of Musk=E2=80=99s stewards=
hip, said about the limits. =E2=80=9CTo set limits so low that it renders t=
he site unusable to average users is just the latest in the purely extracti=
ve approach the new ownership is taking.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh man! Musk, the head of Twitter's <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31975621.257407/aHR0cHM6Ly90=
